FOUND IN: Canter - A three-beat gait that is faster than a trot but slower than a gallop.
Hydration (the process of adding water to something, particularly through soaking, steeping, or absorbing)
Nessie (shortened form for Loch Ness Monster)
Aquiline (historically refers to a curved or Roman-style nose)
Twist - to turn or rotate something in a spiral shape
Tyne - A major river flowing through Jarrow, on its way to meet the North Sea.
Chorale - A simple, harmonized melody often associated with Lutheran church music.
Play on words (a humorous manipulation of language for comedic effect)
Scavenger beetle - While their larvae (grubs) share some characteristics with maggots, they are distinctly different insects belonging to the family Scarabaeidae.
